06693nam a22009375i 9783110796049DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107960497 a10.1515/97831107960492doi  a(DE-B1597)626133  a(OCoLC)1368054130  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE  aIT 5680qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/68537:00aIn the Footsteps of Dante :bCrossroads of European Humanism /ced. by Joao R. Figueiredo, Teresa Bartolomei. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (VIII, 297 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMimesis : Romanische Literaturen der Welt ,x0178-7489 ;v9900tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPrologue -- tWe Are All Called upon to Build Visions -- tSection I: Dante. A Poet of Our Time -- t“Supra te et non subter”: The Biblical Humanism of the Comedy -- tBiblical Signa and Dante’s Words: For a Taxonomy of Biblical Intertextuality in the Comedy -- tDante and the Faith of the Reader -- tDante: Talking to the Dead – Giving a Voice to Silence -- tDante: Memory Matters in the Comedy -- tDante, Poet of a Europe to Come -- tSection II: Dante in Portugal -- tDante in the Century of Camões -- tDante and Camões: Epic and the Portrayal of Humanity -- tDante and the Fifth Empire -- tDante in Portugal: An Ethereal Gaze -- tDante: Poetry and Translation -- tEpilogue -- tDante the Geographer -- tEditions and Translations -- tNotes on Contributors -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDante, the pilgrim, is the image of an author who stubbornly looks ahead, seeking and building the "Great Beyond" (Manguel). Following in his footsteps is therefore not a return to the past, going à rebours, but a commitment to the future, to exploring the potential of humanity to "transhumanise". This dynamic of self-transcendence in Dante’s humanism (Ossola), which claims for European civilisation a vocation for universalism (Ferroni), is analysed in the volume at three crucial moments: Firstly, the establishment of an emancipatory relationship between author and reader (Ascoli), in which authorship is authority and not power; secondly, the conception of vision as a learning process and horizon of eschatological overcoming (Mendonça); finally, the relationship with the past, which is never purely monumental, but ethically and intertextually dynamic, in an original rewriting of the original scriptural, medieval, and classical culture (Nasti, Bolzoni, Bartolomei). A second group of contributions is dedicated to the reconstruction of Dante’s presence in Portuguese literature (Almeida, Espírito Santo, Figueiredo, Marnoto, Vaz de Carvalho): they attest to the innovative impact of Dante’s work even in literary traditions more distant from it.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAlighieri, Dante. 4aChristlicher Humanismus. 4aGöttliche Komödie. 4aPortugiesisch / Literatur.  aAlighieri, Dante.  aChristian humanism.  aDivine Comedy.  aPortuguese literature.1 aAlmeida, Isabel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAscoli, Albert Russell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartolomei, Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartolomei, Teresa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBolzoni, Lina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarvalho, Jorge Vaz de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Mendonça, José Tolentino, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEspírito Santo, Arnaldo do, econtributor.